Can you shoot 4 MOA rapid fire without a bipod or rest?  Can you do it with a rack-grade rifle and surplus ammo?  Can you do it with iron sights?  Join us for an Appleseed Rifle Marksmanship clinic and find out.

See if you can answer these questions - which every American who loves his country should be able to answer:
1. When and where was the American Revolution won, according to John Adams?
2. When and where did the Revolutionary War break out?
3. What caused the British Regulars, the most well-trained, well-disciplined army in the world, to break and run at Concord's North Bridge, after only two minutes of musket fire by shopkeepers and farmers?
4. What caused this reversal of British military opinion:

BEFORE April 19, 1775:
"Americans are raw, undisciplined and cowardly". John Montagu, 4th Earl of Sandwich and 1st Lord of the Admiralty 

"With a thousand British grenadiers I would undertake to go from one end of America to the other and geld all the males, partly by force and partly with a little coaxing". Major General Alured Clarke 

AFTER April 19, 1775:
"Whoever looks upon them as an irregular mob, will find himself very much mistaken. They have men amongst them who know very well what they are about..." Lieutenant-General Hugh Percy, 2nd Duke of Northumberland

Join us on January 12-13, 2013 for the Appleseed Rifle Marksmanship Clinic at Buds Gun Shop, 1105 Industry Road, Lexington, KY  40505 and find out the answers to these basic questions about our country's founding.

title: For Sale:  Custom Colt 1911 45ACP Acc-U-Rails Novak Tritium Sites Etc
postcontent:
Here for sale is a Colt Model 1911 Semi automatic pistol. It started life as one of a thousand special edition Delta Elites that Colt put out in the early ’90s called a ‘Match 10’. These had a Gold Cup lower mated to a government model Delta Elite slide. Serial numbers were MTEN000 – MTEN999.  It was given Novak Tritium night sites and setup for concealed carry. Due to its weight it was seldom carried. 
As the gun was just sitting around a gun smith friend of mine asked if I was interested in having the Match 10 converted to a 460 Roland.  He was interested in trying the new cartridge with a 10mm slide/frame as it was a lot stronger than a stock 45 slide/frame and should not need the compensator the 460 required to keep from beating up the frame of a stock 45 1911. Anyway that meant refacing the slide to fit the 45 ACP case. So now my ‘Match 10’ was rebarreled and chambered in 460 Roland. Yes it worked well at dropping deer like the hammer of Thor but the accuracy was not where the 10mm had been so I had Acc-u-rails installed on the gun which tightened up the groups to excellent and made it much softer to shoot. 
But again due to the weight of the 1911, and now how powerful it shot, I put it away for the last 10 years. Now, in an effort to make the gun both more pleasant to shoot, cheaper to shoot, and sellable, I had a new barrel fit to it in 45 ACP, re-blue it and generally put it back to an ‘As New’ condition Custom Colt 45 1911. 
So here for your consideration is a Delta Elite slide which was factory fitted to a Gold Cup lower, later mated together with Acc-u-rails, further customized with serrations on the front of the slide, Novak night sights, S&A mag well, S&A Ambi Mag release, Brown BeaverTail, Brown Safety, McCormick  Trigger, Pachmayr thumb slide guard, Wilson hammer/sear set and a Wolff Spring Kit throughout. And then re-blued to make all parts match perfectly. 
I am asking $1,500 or a reasonable offer. 
As a high volume competition pistol it should shoot 45ACP forever and never shoot loose. I still have the 460 barrel and bushing which I will include along with the proper spring recommendations, if you are interested.

I have a wilcom F6222 hand held fiber identifier. Bought it new for over $1800 from wilcom. Its still new in the box it came in with all original paper work. Never got a chance to use it b/c I changed careers. Need to get some of my money back out of it. Comes with 3 different interchangeable adapter heads to accommodate; 900 µm buffered fiber, ribbon or 250µm coated fiber and 3mm jacketed fiber. text/call 316 308 six800. thanks


The Wilcom Model F6222 Telecom Optical Fiber Identifier is a rugged, easy-to-use installation and maintenance instrument which identifies optical fibers by detecting the optical signals being transmitted through a fiber. By utilizing local detection technology (non-destructive macro-bend detection which does not damage or overstress the fiber), this units eliminates the need to open the fiber at the splice point for identification; eliminating the probability of interrupting service. 

This Optical Fiber Identifier detects low frequency tones at 270 Hz, 1000 Hz and 2000 Hz. When traffic is present on the fiber under test, an audible tone can be heard as well as the traffic direction which is indicated by LEDs illuminating on the probe. 

During installations, maintenance, rerouting, or restorations it is often necessary to isolate a specific fiber without disrupting service. A light source such as Wilcom's Model FS1316 used in conjunction with the Optical Fiber Identifiers can make the job a lot easier.
